# Claude Code CLI
#
# Claude Code reads MCP servers from ~/.mcp.json or via the --mcp-config flag.
# We reuse the MCP configuration generated at ~/.config/mcp/mcp.json by
# aliasing `claude` in a zsh snippet sourced from ~/.zshrc.
{ pkgs, lib, ... }:
{
  imports = [ ../mcp ];

  home.packages = [ pkgs.claude-code ];

  home.file.".claude/settings.json".text = lib.generators.toJSON { } {
    theme = "dark";
    model = "claude-opus-4-8[1m]";
    skipDangerousModePermissionPrompt = true;
    includeCoAuthoredBy = false;
    effortLevel = "xhigh";
    env = {
      CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_ALTERNATE_SCREEN = "1";
      CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_FEEDBACK_SURVEY = "1";
    };
  };

  xdg.configFile."zsh/claude.zsh".text = ''
    alias claude="claude --mcp-config ~/.config/mcp/mcp.json --dangerously-skip-permissions"
  '';
}

content.text:
I found the exact cause by decompiling the Claude Code 2.1.175 binary. This isn't a home-manager problem — your config is applied correctly.

## Why you see `high`

Opus 4.8 has a **"launch effort pin"** that is *on by default*. While the pin is active, Claude Code forces a per-model launch-default effort and **ignores your `effortLevel` setting entirely**. The decompiled logic:

```js
function launchDefaultEffort(model){
  if (model === "claude-fable-5")  return "high";
  if (model === "claude-opus-4-8") return "high";   // ← your model
  if (model === "claude-opus-4-7") return "xhigh";
  return "high";
}

function effectiveEffort(model, settingsEffort){
  const pinned       = !config.unpinOpus48LaunchEffort;        // true by default
  const launchValue  = launchDefaultEffort(model);            // "high"
  const env          = process.env.CLAUDE_CODE_EFFORT_LEVEL;

  if (env == null) return pinned ? launchValue : undefined;    // ← settingsEffort never consulted!
  let f = env ?? (pinned ? launchValue : undefined) ?? settingsEffort ?? launchValue;
  if (f === "xhigh" && !supportsXhigh(model)) return "high";
  return f;
}
```

So with the env var unset and the pin active, it returns `"high"` and never looks at your `effortLevel:"xhigh"`. Note `KK()` strips the `[1m]` suffix, so the 1M variant behaves identically. Quirk: Opus **4.7**'s launch default is `xhigh`, which is why this only bites on 4.8.

The pin is cleared (`unpinOpus48LaunchEffort: true`) when you interactively change effort via `/effort` — but that writes to `~/.claude.json`/`settings.json`, and **your `/effort` failed** because `settings.json` is a read-only symlink into the nix store. That's the second symptom you hit.

## The fix

The env var `CLAUDE_CODE_EFFORT_LEVEL` has top precedence and beats the pin (Opus 4.8 does support `xhigh`). It fits cleanly into your existing `env` block:

input.new_string:
env = {
  CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_ALTERNATE_SCREEN = "1";
  CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_FEEDBACK_SURVEY = "1";
  # effortLevel above is ignored while Opus 4.8's "launch effort pin"
  # is active (it forces the per-model default of "high"). The env var
  # takes top precedence and overrides the pin.
  CLAUDE_CODE_EFFORT_LEVEL = "xhigh";
};

